---
import BaseLayout from '../../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Model Structure & Components — URDF Format & Model Description"
  description="Take URDF apart and look at its core elements: Link, Joint, Visual, Collision, and Inertial — plus the often-overlooked details of position and orientation that bring a robot model together."
  lang="en"
>
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container urdf-structure">
      <a class="back-link" href="/">&larr; Back to Home</a>

      <header class="detail-header">
        <h1 class="detail-title">Taking It Apart: How a URDF Model Comes Together</h1>
        <p class="detail-subtitle">
          As mentioned earlier, URDF is like a digital blueprint for a robot. It tells the computer
          which parts the robot has, how those parts connect, and how the model should be loaded
          and used. If we take a full URDF apart, the most important pieces fall into two main groups.
        </p>
      </header>

      <!-- Section: Intro overview -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">The Two Main Building Blocks of URDF</h2>
      <div class="overview-grid">
        <div class="overview-card">
          <p class="overview-tag">Part 1</p>
          <h3 class="overview-title">Link and Joint</h3>
          <p class="overview-desc">
            These build the structure of the robot. A Link is a part, and a Joint is what connects
            those parts together.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="overview-card">
          <p class="overview-tag">Part 2</p>
          <h3 class="overview-title">Visual, Collision, and Inertial</h3>
          <p class="overview-desc">
            These add appearance, collision, and physics information to each part — so the model
            isn't just visible, but can also behave correctly in a simulator.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout-card">
        <p class="callout-text">
          You can also think of it like assembling a robot: first build each individual part, then
          connect them together, and finally fill in their appearance and basic physical
          information. That way the model is not only something you can see, but something that
          can actually work properly inside a simulator.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Link -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Link: A Part of the Robot</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        In URDF, a Link can be thought of as a single part of the robot. The base, an arm, a
        forearm, a wheel, a gripper — each of these can be a link.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        You can think of a Link as a <strong>"body part"</strong> or a <strong>"skeleton piece"</strong>
        of the robot. With only Links, the robot is just a pile of separate parts — not yet a
        complete structure.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Inside a Link in URDF, you'll often see a few important sub-elements:
      </p>

      <div class="concept-grid concept-grid--three">
        <div class="concept-card">
          <h3 class="concept-label">Visual</h3>
          <p class="concept-desc">What it looks like</p>
        </div>
        <div class="concept-card">
          <h3 class="concept-label">Collision</h3>
          <p class="concept-desc">How its collision area is calculated</p>
        </div>
        <div class="concept-card">
          <h3 class="concept-label">Inertial</h3>
          <p class="concept-desc">Its weight and physical properties</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Note that not every link will have all of these filled in. In simple models, sometimes
        only the appearance is defined; the collision and physics information is usually added
        later when simulation is needed.
      </p>

      <!-- Section: Joint -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Joint: What Connects the Parts</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If a Link is a part, a Joint is the place where parts connect. Its job is important
        because it tells the computer:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Which two Links are connected</li>
        <li>How they can move relative to each other</li>
        <li>Where the joint is mounted</li>
        <li>Which axis it moves along</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        In other words, a Joint isn't just about "connecting" — it also defines how the entire
        robot moves.
      </p>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        You can also think of the whole robot as a tree: starting from the base, parts grow
        outward one by one. That's why inside a Joint, you'll often see <strong>Parent</strong>
        and <strong>Child</strong> notation.
      </p>

      <div class="relation-grid">
        <div class="relation-card relation-card--parent">
          <p class="relation-tag">Parent</p>
          <p class="relation-desc">The upper, "main body" link</p>
          <p class="relation-example">For example: shoulder, axle</p>
        </div>
        <div class="relation-arrow" aria-hidden="true">↓</div>
        <div class="relation-card relation-card--child">
          <p class="relation-tag">Child</p>
          <p class="relation-desc">The link attached underneath that follows along</p>
          <p class="relation-example">For example: arm, wheel</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Joint types -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Common Joint Types</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        There's more than one kind of Joint. Different joint types decide whether parts can move
        and how they move. For getting started, these four are the most useful to be familiar with.
      </p>

      <ol class="stage-list">
        <li class="stage-item">
          <span class="stage-num">1</span>
          <div class="stage-body">
            <h3 class="stage-title">Fixed</h3>
            <p class="stage-desc">
              This kind of Joint doesn't move — it locks two parts together. If two parts are
              meant to stay still relative to each other, Fixed is usually the right choice.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="stage-item">
          <span class="stage-num">2</span>
          <div class="stage-body">
            <h3 class="stage-title">Revolute</h3>
            <p class="stage-desc">
              This kind of Joint can rotate, but only within an angle limit. It's a lot like an
              elbow or a knee — it can only turn within a certain range.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="stage-item">
          <span class="stage-num">3</span>
          <div class="stage-body">
            <h3 class="stage-title">Continuous</h3>
            <p class="stage-desc">
              This kind of Joint also rotates, but without an angle limit. The most common
              example is a wheel, since wheels usually need to spin freely.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="stage-item">
          <span class="stage-num">4</span>
          <div class="stage-body">
            <h3 class="stage-title">Prismatic</h3>
            <p class="stage-desc">
              This kind of Joint doesn't rotate — it slides in a straight line. You can think of
              it like pulling a drawer out and pushing it back in.
            </p>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ol>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        There are other joint types too, but for getting started, getting comfortable with these
        four will already take you a long way.
      </p>

      <!-- Section: Visual -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Visual: What It Looks Like</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Visual is responsible for the model's appearance. In short, it defines what this part
        looks like on screen. Things you can set here include:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>Geometric shape — for example, a box, cylinder, or sphere</li>
        <li>Color</li>
        <li>Material</li>
        <li>Importing a 3D model file</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So Visual is mainly for people to see and for the screen to display. When we look at a
        robot's appearance inside a simulator, what we're seeing is mostly the Visual part doing
        its job.
      </p>

      <!-- Section: Collision -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Collision: How Collisions Are Calculated</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Collision tells the computer roughly where this part's "physical extent" is.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        With Collision defined, the simulator can tell whether the model is bumping into the
        floor, walls, or other objects. Without a proper collision area, the model might just
        pass through things like a ghost.
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          <strong>Collision doesn't have to look exactly the same as Visual.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        In many cases, Visual is made more detailed so the model looks nice on screen, while
        Collision is intentionally kept simple — wrapping the part in a box, a cylinder, or some
        other simplified shell.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        This isn't laziness — it's actually a very common practice. The simpler the collision
        model, the more stable the simulation tends to be, and the faster it runs.
      </p>

      <!-- Section: Inertial -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Inertial: The Model's Physical Information</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        Inertial is responsible for the part's basic physical information. If you're only drawing
        the model, missing Inertial may not show an immediate problem — but as soon as physics
        simulation gets involved, this part becomes very important.
      </p>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        It usually affects things like:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>How heavy the part is</li>
        <li>Roughly where its center of mass is</li>
        <li>How much rotational inertia it has</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        These settings affect the model's balance, the forces acting on it, and how it moves in
        simulation. If they're set strangely, the robot may look unstable, fall over easily, or
        move in ways that feel unnatural.
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          So you can think of Inertial as: the information that makes a model not just
          <strong>"look real"</strong>, but also <strong>"move like it's real"</strong>.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Section: Position and direction -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Knowing Link and Joint Isn't Enough — Position and Orientation Matter Too</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        When beginners first start learning URDF, the things they usually pick up first are:
      </p>
      <ul class="check-list">
        <li>There are links</li>
        <li>There are joints</li>
        <li>Joints come in different types</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        All of that is correct, but there's one important detail that's often overlooked:
      </p>

      <div class="highlight-card">
        <p class="highlight-text">
          <strong>Where the joint is mounted, and which axis it moves along.</strong>
        </p>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        If these aren't set correctly, common symptoms look like this:
      </p>
      <ul class="cross-list">
        <li>The arm rotates in a strange direction</li>
        <li>The wheel spins at an angle</li>
        <li>Parts connect at the wrong location</li>
        <li>The whole model looks crooked</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        So when actually writing URDF, beyond the parts and joints themselves,
        <strong>"position" and "orientation"</strong> are also a very important piece of the picture.
      </p>

      <!-- Section: Summary -->
      <h2 class="detail-heading">Summary</h2>
      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        At its simplest, the core work of a URDF file is really just doing two things over and over:
      </p>

      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <p class="summary-step">Step 1</p>
          <h3 class="summary-title">Build the parts</h3>
          <p class="summary-desc">
            Use <strong>Link</strong> to define each part of the robot, then add to each part:
          </p>
          <ul class="summary-list">
            <li><strong>Visual</strong> — what it looks like</li>
            <li><strong>Collision</strong> — how its collision area is calculated</li>
            <li><strong>Inertial</strong> — how its physical information is set</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <p class="summary-step">Step 2</p>
          <h3 class="summary-title">Connect the parts</h3>
          <p class="summary-desc">
            Use <strong>Joint</strong> to link these parts together, and tell the computer:
          </p>
          <ul class="summary-list">
            <li>Which connects to which</li>
            <li>What kind of joint it is</li>
            <li>Where the joint is mounted</li>
            <li>Which axis it moves along</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="detail-paragraph">
        As these two things gradually come together, the model of a robot becomes more and more complete.
      </p>

    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .urdf-structure {
    max-width: 52rem;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    text-decoration: underline;
  }

  /* Header */
  .detail-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-12);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-6);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-title {
    font-size: var(--text-3xl);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    line-height: 1.3;
  }

  .detail-subtitle {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  /* Section headings */
  .detail-heading {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-top: var(--space-12);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
    padding-bottom: var(--space-2);
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  }

  .detail-paragraph {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }

  .detail-paragraph strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Check list */
  .check-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .check-list li {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .check-list li::before {
    content: '\2713';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  /* Cross list (✗ items) */
  .cross-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .cross-list li {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .cross-list li::before {
    content: '\2717';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  /* Callout card */
  .callout-card {
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-8);
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8);
    border-left: 4px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
  }

  .callout-text {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.9;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .callout-text strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Highlight card (for important takeaways — replaces red text) */
  .highlight-card {
    margin: var(--space-4) 0 var(--space-6);
    padding: var(--space-5) var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
  }

  .highlight-text {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: var(--color-heading);
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin: 0;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .highlight-text strong {
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  /* Overview grid (Link & Joint / Visual Collision Inertial intro) */
  .overview-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .overview-card {
    padding: var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    transition: all var(--transition);
  }

  .overview-card:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .overview-tag {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: var(--space-1) var(--space-3);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    background-color: var(--color-tag-bg);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  .overview-title {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .overview-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  /* Concept grid (Visual / Collision / Inertial) */
  .concept-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-8);
  }

  .concept-grid--three {
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  }

  .concept-card {
    padding: var(--space-6);
    border: 2px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    transition: all var(--transition);
  }

  .concept-card:hover {
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }

  .concept-label {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
  }

  .concept-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  /* Relation (Parent / Child) */
  .relation-grid {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    gap: var(--space-3);
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-8);
  }

  .relation-card {
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 28rem;
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    text-align: center;
  }

  .relation-card--parent {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .relation-card--child {
    border-color: var(--color-border);
    background-color: var(--color-bg);
  }

  .relation-tag {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
  }

  .relation-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .relation-example {
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.6;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .relation-arrow {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    color: var(--color-accent);
    line-height: 1;
  }

  /* Stage list (numbered Joint types) */
  .stage-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-6);
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-4);
  }

  .stage-item {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-start;
    gap: var(--space-6);
    padding: var(--space-6) var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
    transition: all var(--transition);
  }

  .stage-item:hover {
    border-color: var(--color-accent);
  }

  .stage-num {
    flex-shrink: 0;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    width: 2.5rem;
    height: 2.5rem;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background-color: var(--color-accent);
    color: #fff;
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .stage-body {
    flex: 1;
    min-width: 0;
  }

  .stage-title {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .stage-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  /* Summary grid (final two-step recap) */
  .summary-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr;
    gap: var(--space-4);
    margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-6);
  }

  .summary-card {
    padding: var(--space-8);
    border: 1px solid var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    background-color: var(--color-bg-secondary);
  }

  .summary-step {
    display: inline-block;
    padding: var(--space-1) var(--space-3);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
    font-size: var(--text-xs);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #fff;
    background-color: var(--color-accent);
    border-radius: var(--border-radius);
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
  }

  .summary-title {
    font-size: var(--text-lg);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: var(--color-heading);
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .summary-desc {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3);
  }

  .summary-desc strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .summary-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .summary-list li {
    font-size: var(--text-sm);
    color: var(--color-text);
    line-height: 1.8;
    padding-left: var(--space-6);
    position: relative;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-2);
  }

  .summary-list li::before {
    content: '\2713';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: var(--color-accent);
    font-weight: 700;
  }

  .summary-list strong {
    color: var(--color-heading);
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Mobile */
  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .overview-grid,
    .concept-grid,
    .concept-grid--three,
    .summary-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }

    .stage-item {
      gap: var(--space-4);
      padding: var(--space-6);
    }

    .stage-num {
      width: 2rem;
      height: 2rem;
      font-size: var(--text-sm);
    }

    .overview-card,
    .summary-card {
      padding: var(--space-6);
    }

    .relation-card {
      padding: var(--space-5) var(--space-6);
    }

    .highlight-card {
      padding: var(--space-4) var(--space-6);
    }

    .highlight-text {
      font-size: var(--text-sm);
    }
  }
</style>
